# what is modules?
A module is a reusable block of Terraform code.
modules/
   └── ec2/
        ├── main.tf
        ├── variables.tf
        ├── outputs.tf

# what is variables?
Variables are like placeholders.

Instead of hardcoding values (like instance type, region, name), we use variables so we can reuse the code.

instance_type = var.instance_type

# What is provider?
A provider is a plugin that allows Terraform to talk to a specific platform.

provider "aws" {
  region = "ap-south-1"
}

# What is resource?
A resource is the actual infrastructure you want to create.

resource "PROVIDER_RESOURCE_TYPE" "NAME" {
  arguments
}

resource "TYPE" "NAME"



# what is variables.tf?
variables.tf is the file where you define input variables for your Terraform project.
It does NOT store values (usually).
It defines the structure of the inputs.
variable "region" {
  description = "AWS region"
  type        = string
}

variable "instance_type" {
  description = "EC2 instance type"
  type        = string
  default     = "t2.micro"
}

variable "environment" {
  description = "Environment name"
  type        = string
}

# what is .tfvars file?
.tfvars file is where you assign actual values to variables.

region        = "ap-south-1"
instance_type = "t2.medium"
environment   = "dev"


# Terraform File Types
main.tf = Main configuration files.

variables.tf = Defines input variables.

terraform.tfvars = Assigns values to variables.

outputs.tf = Displays output values.

terraform.tfstate = Stores infrastructure state (VERY IMPORTANT).

# State File (terraform.tfstate)
Stores: What Terraform created
Resource IDs
Metadata
Without state file → Terraform is blind.

# Terraform Commands
terraform init = Initialize project.
terraform plan = Shows what will change.
terraform apply = Creates or updates infra.
terraform destroy = Deletes infra.
terraform validate = Checks syntax.
terraform fmt = Formats code.
terraform state list = to list resources in state file.
terraform state show RESOURCE_NAME = to show details of a resource in state file.


# Data Sources
Fetch existing resources.

data "aws_ami" "latest" {}

# Backend: Backend stores state.

Types: gautam-terraform-demo-bucket-12345
Local
S3
Azure Storage
Terraform Cloud

Production → Always remote backend.

# State Locking
Prevents two people from running apply at same time.

# Count
Creates multiple resources.

count = 3


# ================================= connect terraform with OIDC github (without aws credentials) ================================= provider "aws" { region = "ap-south-1" # OIDC configuration assume_role { role_arn = "arn:aws:iam::123456789012:role/GitHubActionsRole" session_name = "GitHubActionsSession" } }


1. Create a repo in github name terraform-oidc and clone it to server.

2. creat OIDC provider in AWS IAM.
Iam -> Identity providers -> Add provider -> OIDC -> provider URL: https://token.actions.githubusercontent.com audience: sts.amazonaws.com

3. create role with trust relationship to OIDC providers
Iam -> Roles -> Create role -> Web Identity -> select OIDC provider created in step 1 -> select "sts.amazonaws.com" as audience -> organization (github username) -> Next -> attach policies (like administratoraccess) -> Next -> Role name: OIDC-terraform -> Create role
role -> edit trust relationship
{
	"Version": "2012-10-17",
	"Statement": [
		{
			"Effect": "Allow",
			"Principal": {
				"Federated": "arn:aws:iam::831926612453:oidc-provider/token.actions.githubusercontent.com"
			},
			"Action": "sts:AssumeRoleWithWebIdentity",
			"Condition": {
				"StringEquals": {
					"token.actions.githubusercontent.com:aud": "sts.amazonaws.com",
					"token.actions.githubusercontent.com:sub": "repo:Gautamkathuria/terraform-oidc:ref:refs/heads/main"
				}
			}
		}
	]
}

4. now copy the configuration files to clone repo using cp and push to github by removing
.terraform and terrafrom.statefiles.

5. now create a github workflow in .github/workflows/terraform.yml

name: Terraform CI/CD

on:
  push:
    branches:
      - main
  pull_request:
    branches:
      - main

jobs:
  terraform:
    runs-on: ubuntu-latest
    permissions:
      id-token: write
      contents: read

    steps:
      - name: Checkout Repo
        uses: actions/checkout@v3

      - name: Setup Terraform
        uses: hashicorp/setup-terraform@v2
        with:
          terraform_version: 1.6.0

      # Configure AWS credentials using OIDC
      - name: Configure AWS credentials via OIDC
        uses: aws-actions/configure-aws-credentials@v3
        with:
          role-to-assume: arn:aws:iam::831926612453:role/oidc-terraform 
          aws-region: us-east-1

      - name: Terraform Init
        working-directory: ./awss3
        run: terraform init

      - name: Terraform Plan
        working-directory: ./awss3
        run: terraform plan -var-file="file.auto.tfvars"

      - name: Terraform Apply
        if: github.ref == 'refs/heads/main'
        working-directory: ./awss3
        run: terraform apply -auto-approve -var-file="file.auto.tfvars"

6. now run the github actions, it will create the infrastructure in AWS without using any credentials.



